abstract: The vice chairman of G.M. said that Toyota had “more congressmen and senators” fighting for its interests, because it had built new factories in a large number of states.
snippet: The vice chairman of G.M. said that Toyota had “more congressmen and senators” fighting for its interests, because it had built new factories in a large number of states.
lead_paragraph: DETROIT, Jan. 9 — Toyota has not yet passed General Motors to become the world’s biggest carmaker, but Robert A. Lutz, G.M.’s vice chairman, says his company has fallen behind its rival in terms of clout on Capitol Hill.

headline.main: G.M. Officer Says Toyota Is Stronger in Washington
headline.print_headline: G.M. Officer Says Toyota Is Stronger in Washington
